03611nmm a2200553Ia 9780520914568DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209145687 a10.1525/97805209145682doi  a(DE-B1597)544018  a(OCoLC)1149478097  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0110002bisacsh04a398.2/0899741 aBahr, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Short, Swift Time of Gods on Earth :bThe Hohokam Chronicles /cWilliam Smith Allison, Juan Smith, Donald Bahr, Julian Hayden.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the spring of 1935, at Snaketown, Arizona, two Pima Indians recounted and translated their entire traditional creation narrative. Juan Smith, reputedly the last tribesman with extensive knowledge of the Pima version of this story, spoke and sang while William Smith Allison translated into English and Julian Hayden, an archaeologist, recorded Allison's words verbatim. The resulting document, the "Hohokam Chronicles," is the most complete natively articulated Pima creation narrative ever written and a rare example of a single-narrator myth.Now this extraordinary work, composed of thirty-six separate stories, is presented in its entirety for the first time. Beautifully expressed, the narrative constitutes a kind of scripture for a native church, beginning with the creation of the universe out of the void and ending with the establishment in the sixteenth century of present-day villages. Central to the story is the murder/resurrection of a god-man, Siuuhu, who summoned the Pimas and Papagos (Tohono O'odham) as his army of vengeance and brought about the conquest of his murderers, the ancient Hohokam.Donald Bahr extensively annotates the text and supplements it with other Pima-Papago versions of similar stories. Important as a social and historic document, this book adds immeasurably to the growing body of Native American literature and to our knowledge of the development of Pima-Papago culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHohokam culture. 0aPima IndiansvFolklore. 0aPima IndiansxFolklore. 0aTohono O'odham IndiansvFolklore. 0aTohono O'odham IndiansxFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh1 aAllison, William Smith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, Juan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520914568?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914568/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles